Qg4 Ne5 17. Qh5 Nc6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qg5+ Kh8 20. Qf6+ $11 {Draw by perpetual
check.}) 16... Be5 17. Rhe1 (17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Rhe1 Nc5 19. Nxc5 Qxc5 20. Qe5
Qxe5 21. Rxe5 Bb7 $11 {Black does not have any problem. This endgame is equal.}
) 17... Bxd4 18. Rxd4 Bb7 19. Qd3 (19. Ng5 Nc5 $1 20. Nxh7 {After this knight
sacrifice Black has two options, either to accept the sacrifice or declining
it with ...Rdf8. Both results in a draw.} Rfd8 $5 (20... Kxh7 {Leads to a draw.
} 21. Qh5+ Kg8 22. Rh4 f6 23. Ba2 $1 Rfe8 24. Qh8+ Kf7 25. Qh5+ Kg8 (25... Ke7
26. Qg4 $44 {The position is very complicated and White has compensation.}) 26.
Qh8+ Kf7 27. Qh5+ $11 {Draw by perpetual check.}) 21. Rh4 Nxb3 22. cxb3 (22.
Nf6+ Kf8 23. Nh7+ Kg8 $11 {Draw by perpetual check.}) 22... Qc5 $1 {After this
move both sides have to play accurately. After a long and forcing variation,
the game ends in a draw by perpetual check.} 23. f4 Qf5+ 24. Ka1 Rd4 25. Ng5
Rxf4 26. Rxf4 Qxf4 27. Qh5 Bxg2 28. Qh7+ Kf8 29. Rxe6 Qc1+ 30. Ka2 fxe6 31.
Qh8+ Ke7 32. Qxg7+ Kd6 33. Nf7+ Kc6 34. Ne5+ Kd6 35. Nf7+ $11 {Draw by
perpetual check.}) 19... Nc5 20. Nxc5 Qxc5 $13 {After exchanging the knights
White has no chances to organize a dangerous attack. Black has a comfortable
position.}) 12... dxe5 13. Bxe5 (13. Qxe5 Qd6 14. Qxd6 $146 {This novelty is
better than the game and White equalizes without any problems.} (14. Qe3 Qc6
15. g4 {1/2 (22) Steudel,K (2260)-Schmid,S (2280) Austria 1999} b4 $146 {
After this novelty, Black has a very comfortable position and White has to
make a huge effort to equalize.} 16. g5 Ng4 17. Qe4 Qxe4 18. Nxe4 Bb7 19. Rhe1
Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Bxg5+ 21. f4 Be7 22. Rg1 Nf6 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Rxb4 a5 25. Rc4
Rfd8 $15 {[%csl Rf4,Rh2] White's kingside pawns are weak and despite the
opposite-coloured bishops Black's chances are slightly better.}) 14... Bxd6 15.
Bxf6 Bf4+ 16. Kb1 gxf6 17. Ne4 f5 18. Nf6+ Kh8 19. Nd7 Bxd7 20. Rxd7 Rad8 $11 {
This endgame is equal.}) 13... Qb6 14. Ne4 {After this move White liquidates
the position. Because White will not have the chance to liquidate after Black
plays...Bb7 and the c3 knight could always be harassed by ...b4. Because of
this exchanging the knights is a good idea for White.} (14. Bd4 $6 Qc7 15. Be5
Qc6 $1 {Black does not want to do a draw by repetition because Black does not
have any problem and has a comfortable position.} 16. Rhe1 Bb7 17. Rd3 b4 18.
Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Ne4 {1/2 (26) Dijkhuis,T (2313)-Firat,B (2467) Paleochora 2015}
Be7 $1 $146 {After this strong novelty Black keeps the bishop pair advantage.
White's rook entered the attack from the third rank and although it seems
White has a strong attack, he does not have any serious threats. Black's
bishop pair is very powerful and controls many important squares.} 20. Qh5 (20.
Rg3 Rad8 21. Qg4 g6 22. Qf4 {[%cal Gf4h6]} Kg7 $1 23. Qe5+ f6 24. Qxe6 Qxe6 25.
Bxe6 Rfe8 $19 {[%cal Gf6f5] Black's bishop pair is fantastic and Black has so
many threats. White's position is objectively lost.}) 20... Qc7 {[%cal Gc7f4]
Black wants to play ...Qf4.} 21. g3 {White has prevented Black's idea with
this move but White rook has no way to join the attack.} a5 {[%cal Ga5a4]
Black is threatening to play ...a4.} 22. Ba4 g6 23. Qh6 Rfd8 $17 {Black is
clearly better.}) 14... Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Bg5+ $1 {This intermezzo is very
important.} (15... Bb7 $2 16. Qg4 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gd1d7] After Black
prevents the threat of mate with 16...g6 White will play 27. Rd7. White is
clearly better.}) 16. f4 {This is the most logical move.} (16. Kb1 Bb7 17. Qg4
Bh6 {Black was not forced to weaken the position by pushing ...g6. Now Black
is ready to get a counterplay by pushing ...a5.} 18. Qg3 a5 $146 {[%cal Ga5a4]
Black is threatening to play ...a4.} 19. Rd4 {[%cal Gd4h4] With this move
White wants to play Rh4. Now the game becomes forced and at the end of a long
variation the game ends in a draw by repetition.} a4 20. Rh4 axb3 21. Rxh6
bxc2+ 22. Kc1 f6 23. Rxf6 Rxf6 24. Bxf6 g6 25. Re1 Rxa2 26. Qb8+ Kf7 27. Qf4
Ke8 28. Qb8+ Kf7 29. Qf4 Ke8 $11 {Draw by move repetition.}) 16... Bb7 17. Qe2
Bh6 18. Kb1 (18. Rhg1 $146 {White is prepared to play g4 with this move. But
Black's queenside play give very good chances.} a5 19. g4 g6 {[%cal Ga5a4]} 20.
a3 a4 21. Ba2 b4 $132 {Black has a very good counterplay.}) (18. Rd6 $146 {
White wants to double his rooks on the d-file.} Qc5 19. Rhd1 a5 $1 {[%cal
Ga5a4] Black threatens to play ...a4. Now white has to decide either to play
20.c3 or 20.a3 to create a room for the bishop.} 20. c3 (20. a3 Bxg2 {With
this nice trick Black wins a pawn and I think White does not have enough
compensation.} 21. Kb1 (21. Qxg2 $2 {is a blunder and after} Qxe5 $19 {Black
is winning.}) 21... Bh3 22. Rd7 a4 23. Ba2 g6 $15 {Black's chances are better.}
) 20... b4 21. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} g6 22. Kb1 bxc3 23. Bxc3 Bg7 24. Bxg7 Kxg7
$132 {Black has a comfortable position.}) 18... Rfd8 19. c3 Qc6 20. Rhg1 $2 {
1/2 (50) Panbukchian,V (2380)-Ermenkov,E (2480) Bulgaria 1988} (20. Rxd8+ $146
{This improvement would be normal and after} Rxd8 21. Rd1 $11 {White's
equalising without any problems.}) 20... Rxd1+ $146 {Black misses a big
opportunity by not playing this move. After this novelty White loses a pawn in
all variations.} 21. Rxd1 (21. Bxd1 f6 22. Bd4 Qe4+ 23. Qxe4 Bxe4+ 24. Bc2
Bxc2+ 25. Kxc2 Bxf4 $17 {Black is a clear pawn up and he has a good position.})
(21. Qxd1 Bxf4 $1 $17 {Black wins a move with this tactics and keeps a clear
